The group formed originally in the latter half of 2013 as a collaborative songwriting and recording relationship between William Rutledge (Suns, Poverty Hollow) and Sam Skinner (Pinegrove, Tawny Peaks). Almost immediately, drummer Victor Massari and bassist Mike Dvorscak joined the two, and PUPPPY established itself as a consistently powerful and effective live band in the New York, Hudson Valley and Connecticut circuits. 

PUPPPY's debut full-length album, Shit in the Apple Pie was released as a cassette on Father/Daughter Records in April of 2015. SITAPgarnered national acclaim, with publications such as VICE praising its "reliable (but never derivative) pop song structures to make something unique". Stereogum added praise, saying "Rutledge's genius lies in his storytelling abilities" delivered with a "voice that practically wilts with earnestness." Since the release of SITAP, PUPPPY embarked on a six-and-a-half week full US tour with label-mates DOUBLES (formerly O-FACE) and have continued to light up shows with dynamic and engaging performances in and around the Northeast. 

PUPPPY's music arrives at a point of tension between introspection and extroversion. Built upon a foundation of warm and driving acoustic guitar, the compositions range from delicate guitar work and angelic harmonies, to bombastic choruses and dissonant verses. Rutledge's lyrics are both painful and beautiful, influenced by his undergraduate Philosophy studies and interest in psychoanalytic ideas. They meditate on the the subtextual, sublime, and scary moments inherent in everyday life concerning love, fear, and forgiveness. 

PUPPPY reentered the studio in the tail end of 2015 to record their sophomore LP Gooey Function for an expected late 2016 release, with a rigorous tour schedule in place for the entirety of the year.
